**Deterministic (noise-free) entropy**

\[
\boxed{\;
h^{(0)}(T)\;=\;
-\!\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\rho^{(0)}(x,T)\,
\log \rho^{(0)}(x,T)\,dx
\;=\;
h^{(0)}(0)\;+\;\int_{0}^{T}\!
\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho^{(0)}(s)}\,ds
\;}
\]

where \(\rho^{(0)}(x,T)\) solves the Liouville equation  
\(\partial_{t}\rho^{(0)}=-\nabla\!\cdot(f\rho^{(0)})\) and  
\(\displaystyle\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\rangle_{\rho^{(0)}(s)}
=\int (\nabla\!\cdot f)\,\rho^{(0)}(x,s)\,dx\).

---

**Instantaneous entropy rate in the noisy system**

\[
\boxed{\;
\partial_{t}h^{\varepsilon}(T)
\;=\;
\varepsilon^{2}\,\mathcal I\!\bigl[\rho^{\varepsilon}(T)\bigr]
\;+\;
\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho^{\varepsilon}(T)}
\;}
\]

via the De Bruijn identity, with  

\[
\mathcal I[\rho^{\varepsilon}]
=\int \rho^{\varepsilon}(x,T)\,
\|\nabla\!\log\rho^{\varepsilon}(x,T)\|^{2}\,dx
\quad\text{(non-parametric Fisher information)},
\]

and \(\rho^{\varepsilon}(x,T)\) solving the Fokker–Planck equation  
\(\partial_{t}\rho^{\varepsilon}
=-\nabla\!\cdot(f\rho^{\varepsilon})+\varepsilon^{2}\Delta\rho^{\varepsilon}\).

\[
\boxed{ \;
h(\varepsilon,0)\;=\;
\Bigl[\,h^{(0)}(0)\;+\;\int_{0}^{T}\!\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho^{(0)}(s)}\,ds\Bigr]
\;+\;(n-D_{I})
\;+\;T\Bigl[\,\varepsilon^{2}\,\mathcal I\!\bigl[\rho^{\varepsilon}(T)\bigr]
\;+\;\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho^{\varepsilon}(T)}\Bigr]
\;+\;O\!\bigl(\varepsilon^{2}+v^{2}\bigr),
\qquad T=\frac{1}{v}\; }
\]

Below is a “from–first-principles’’ route to the small-noise / long-time asymptotics you asked for, using **only** (i) the existence of a global attractor, (ii) the Fokker–Planck equation, and (iii) integration by parts.

---

### 1 Stationary Fokker–Planck and the *balance identity*

Let  
\[
\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}(x)\quad(\varepsilon>0)
\]
be the unique stationary density solving  
\[
-\nabla\!\cdot\bigl(f\,\rho\bigr)+\varepsilon^{2}\,\nabla^{2}\rho\,=\,0,
\qquad
\rho=\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}.
\tag{FP\(_\infty\)}
\]

Multiply \((\text{FP}_\infty)\) by \(\log\rho\) and integrate over \(\mathbb R^{n}\).  
One integration by parts (zero surface terms because \(\rho\) and \(\nabla\rho\) decay super-polynomially off the attractor’s neighbourhood) gives

\[
\boxed{\;
\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}
+\varepsilon^{2}\;
\Bigl\langle\|\nabla\!\log\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}\|^{2}\Bigr\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}
=0\;}
\tag{1}
\]

The second term is the (non-parametric) Fisher information,
\(I^{\varepsilon}_\infty:=\langle\|\nabla\!\log\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}\|^{2}\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}\).

Equation (1) rewrites as  

\[
\boxed{\;
\varepsilon^{2}\,I^{\varepsilon}_\infty
= -\,\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}. \;}
\tag{2}
\]

---

### 2 A de Bruijn-type identity that *is* allowed

Treat \(\sigma^{2}:=\varepsilon^{2}\) as a parameter in \((\text{FP}_\infty)\).  
Differentiate the differential entropy  

\[
h_\infty^{\varepsilon}\;:=\;
-\int_{\mathbb R^{n}}\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}(x)\,
\log\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}(x)\,dx
\]

with respect to \(\sigma^{2}\).  A single integration by parts identical to the one in step 1 yields

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\partial h_\infty^{\varepsilon}}{\partial(\varepsilon^{2})}
=\frac{1}{2}\,I^{\varepsilon}_\infty.\;}
\tag{3}
\]

Formula (3) is the classical de Bruijn identity specialised to the *stationary* solution of the Fokker–Planck equation; no outside stochastic-calculus machinery is needed.

---

### 3 Eliminating \(I_\infty^{\varepsilon}\)

Substitute \(I_\infty^{\varepsilon}\) from (2) into (3):

\[
\frac{\partial h_\infty^{\varepsilon}}{\partial(\varepsilon^{2})}
\;=\;
-\frac{1}{2\,\varepsilon^{2}}\,
\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}.
\tag{4}
\]

---

### 4 Taking the small-noise limit

Because the deterministic flow possesses a global attractor, \(\nabla\!\cdot f\) is bounded on that set; its average under \(\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}\) therefore has a finite limit as \(\varepsilon\to0\).  Define

\[
D_I
\;:=\;
-\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}
\;\;\;\;(\text{well-defined, }0\le D_I\le n).
\tag{5}
\]

(We will recognise \(D_I\) as the *information dimension* below.)

For \(\varepsilon\) sufficiently small one may write  

\[
\bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}
=-D_I+\mathcal O(\varepsilon^{2}),
\tag{6}
\]

which, substituted into (4), integrates immediately:

\[
\begin{aligned}
h_\infty^{\varepsilon}
&= h_\infty^{\varepsilon_0}
-\frac{1}{2}\int_{\varepsilon_0^{2}}^{\varepsilon^{2}}
\frac{D_I+\mathcal O(s)}{s}\,ds \\[4pt]
&= h_\infty^{\varepsilon_0}
+D_I\,\log\!\frac{\varepsilon_0}{\varepsilon}
+\mathcal O(\varepsilon^{2}\log\varepsilon).
\end{aligned}
\tag{7}
\]

Choosing \(\varepsilon_0\) fixed (or absorbing its contribution into a constant) gives the sought **first-order expansion**

\[
\boxed{\;
h_\infty^{\varepsilon}
= C
+ D_I\,\log\!\frac{1}{\varepsilon}
+ \mathcal O(\varepsilon^{2}\log\varepsilon),\qquad
(\varepsilon\to0).\;}
\tag{8}
\]

---

### 5 Consistency with the coarse-grained relation

Your earlier cube-based coarse-graining identity

\[
H^{\varepsilon} = h - D_I\log\varepsilon + \mathcal O(1)
\]

is recovered automatically: inserting (8) shows that the \(\varepsilon\)-divergent part of \(h\) is exactly \(+D_I\log(1/\varepsilon)\), so \(H^{\varepsilon}\) saturates to the constant \(C+\mathcal O(1)\).  Hence

*each stable (transverse) direction contributes one \(\log(1/\varepsilon)\)*,
and the number of such directions is \(D_I\).  
That identifies \(D_I\) with the usual **information dimension of the attractor**.

---

### 6 Leading behaviour of the Fisher term

Combining (2), (6) and (8) one also has

\[
\boxed{\;
I_\infty^{\varepsilon}=\frac{D_I}{\varepsilon^{2}}+\mathcal O(1).}
\tag{9}
\]

The \(1/\varepsilon^{2}\) blow-up is precisely what balances the \(\nabla\!\cdot f\) average in (1).

---

## Summary

* **Entropy:** \(h_\infty^{\varepsilon}=C + D_I\log(1/\varepsilon)+\mathcal O(\varepsilon^{2}\log\varepsilon)\).
* **Fisher information:** \(I_\infty^{\varepsilon}=D_I/\varepsilon^{2}+\mathcal O(1)\).
* **Dynamics–dimension link:** \(D_I=-\displaystyle\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\rangle_{\rho_\infty^{\varepsilon}}\).

Everything follows from the Fokker–Planck equation plus two integrations by parts—no external perturbation series or stochastic-calculus results were used.
